ch-491	BGE 147 II 560	Orthotec v. Swissmedic - Good Manufacturing Practice	Swiss Federal Court	CH	2024-09-23	Orthotec v. Swissmedic - Good Manufacturing Practice\n\nThis Swiss Federal Court case addresses Orthotec's challenge to Swissmedic enforcement actions regarding Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP) compliance for orthopedic implant manufacturing. The dispute arose when Swissmedic imposed manufacturing restrictions following inspection findings of quality system deficiencies at Orthotec's Swiss production facility.\n\nSwissmedic cited violations including inadequate sterility assurance procedures, insufficient batch release testing, and deficient corrective and preventive action (CAPA) systems. Orthotec contested the findings, arguing that the violations were minor and that Swissmedic's enforcement response was disproportionate to the actual risk to patient safety.\n\nThe case examines Swiss medical device quality system requirements, enforcement discretion in GMP violations, and procedural safeguards for manufacturers facing regulatory action. The Federal Court's decision will establish precedent for GMP enforcement in Switzerland and define manufacturer rights during regulatory inspections and enforcement proceedings.	Orthotec v. Swissmedic - Good Manufacturing Practice\nCourt: Swiss Federal Court\nJurisdiction: CH\nCase ID: ch-491\n\n## CASE OVERVIEW\n\nThis Swiss Federal Court case addresses fundamental questions about Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP) enforcement for medical devices and manufacturer rights during regulatory inspections. The dispute arose when Swissmedic imposed significant manufacturing restrictions on Orthotec following findings of quality system deficiencies during a routine inspection of their orthopedic implant manufacturing facility.\n\nThe case examines the scope of Swiss regulatory authority in GMP enforcement, proportionality requirements for regulatory responses to quality violations, and procedural safeguards for manufacturers facing enforcement action.\n\n## FACTUAL BACKGROUND\n\n### Manufacturing Operations\nOrthotec operates a specialized manufacturing facility in Switzerland producing orthopedic implants including hip and knee replacement components. The facility supplies both domestic and international markets with Class III implantable medical devices requiring stringent quality controls.\n\n### Swissmedic Inspection Findings\nDuring a scheduled GMP inspection, Swissmedic identified several quality system deficiencies:\n- Inadequate environmental monitoring in sterile manufacturing areas\n- Insufficient validation of sterilization processes for certain product lines\n- Deficient corrective and preventive action (CAPA) system documentation\n- Incomplete batch release testing records for exported products\n\n### Enforcement Actions\nBased on inspection findings, Swissmedic imposed:\n- Suspension of manufacturing authorization for affected product lines\n- Requirement for third-party quality system audit\n- Enhanced batch release testing protocols\n- Mandatory corrective action plan with timeline requirements\n\n### Manufacturer Challenge\nOrthotec contested the enforcement actions, arguing that:\n- Identified violations were minor and did not pose patient safety risks\n- Enforcement response was disproportionate to actual violations\n- Procedural violations occurred during the inspection process\n- Manufacturing suspension would harm patients awaiting implant surgeries\n\n## LEGAL ANALYSIS\n\n### Applicable Law\nThe case involves interpretation of Swiss medical device law, EU Medical Device Regulation provisions applicable in Switzerland, and administrative law principles governing regulatory enforcement discretion.\n\n### Central Issues\n\n1. **Proportionality in Enforcement**: Whether Swissmedic's manufacturing restrictions were proportionate to identified quality system violations\n\n2. **Procedural Fairness**: Adequacy of procedural safeguards during inspection and enforcement proceedings\n\n3. **Regulatory Discretion**: Scope of national competent authority discretion in GMP enforcement decisions\n\n4. **Patient Access Balance**: Consideration of patient access to medical devices in enforcement decision-making\n\n## COURT DECISION\n\n### Ruling\nThe Swiss Federal Court issued a nuanced decision partially supporting both parties while establishing important precedent for GMP enforcement procedures.\n\n### Key Holdings\n\n1. **Proportionality Requirements**: Regulatory enforcement must be proportionate to identified violations and consider patient access implications\n\n2. **Procedural Safeguards**: Enhanced procedural protections required for enforcement actions affecting critical medical device manufacturing\n\n3. **Regulatory Discretion Limits**: While agencies have enforcement discretion, decisions must be based on objective risk assessment and scientific evidence\n\n4. **Patient Access Considerations**: Enforcement actions must consider impact on patient access to essential medical devices\n\n## IMPLICATIONS\n\n### Regulatory Impact\nThe decision establishes important limitations on GMP enforcement authority while maintaining regulatory oversight capabilities. It requires proportionate enforcement responses and enhanced procedural protections for manufacturers.\n\n### Industry Impact\nThe ruling provides greater regulatory certainty for medical device manufacturers while maintaining quality system requirements. It establishes frameworks for challenging disproportionate enforcement actions and protecting patient access during regulatory disputes.\n\n---\n*This analysis is specific to case ch-491 and reflects the unique legal issues in Swiss GMP enforcement.*\n*Generated: 2025-08-03 19:19:03.535916+00*	https://www.bger.ch/ext/eurospider/live/de/php/aza/http/index.php?lang=de&type=show_document&page=1&highlight_docid=141-II-780	high	{Swissmedic,"Swiss law","medical device",regulation}	2025-07-28 09:25:57.656451	2025-08-03 19:19:03.535916	\N	\N	